# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1884-new-york-metropolitans-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1883-new-york-metropolitans-season] The **1883 New York Metropolitans** finished with a 54–42 record, finishing in fourth place in the American Association.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1883-new-york-metropolitans-season] This was the first season in the Association for the Metropolitans, who had previously played as an independent team from 1880–1882.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1883-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1883 Philadelphia Athletics** finished with a 66–32 record and won the championship of the American Association.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1884-baltimore-monumentals-season] The **1884 Baltimore Monumentals** finished with a 58–47 record in the Union Association, finishing in fourth place.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1884-baltimore-monumentals-season] This was the only season this version of the team existed, and indeed the only season the Union Association existed.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1884-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1884 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 14th season of the franchise.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1884-boston-reds-season] The **1884 Boston Reds** finished with a 58–51 record in the Union Association, finishing in fifth place (fourth among teams that played a full schedule).
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1884-boston-reds-season] This was the only season the team existed, and indeed the only season the Union Association existed.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1884-new-york-metropolitans-season] The **1884 New York Metropolitans** finished with a 75–32 record, first place in the American Association.
[src:1884-new-york-metropolitans-season/1884-new-york-metropolitans-season] After the season, they played the National League champion Providence Grays in the 1884 World Series and lost three games to zero.
